export const VSG_PLAYBOOK_CONTENT = "NO HITL DI Video Script\nGenerator v2 (Experiment)\nThe DI Video Script Generator is a tab in the Curriculum Scoping Tool. A user\npicks a generated course, multi-selects lessons, and generates. For each lesson,\nthe system combines the lesson card, the Stein textbook, and this rulebook into a\ncolor-coded, production-ready script for a video that explicitly teaches the\nlessonʼs concept to one student, self-paced, at a computer — model first, then\nguided participation through checked interactions.\nWhat a video is: explicit model →  guided participation — brisk, high-success,\ngrounded in symbols, computation, and correct math vocabulary — that teaches\nthe concept thoroughly enough for the student to transfer the strategy to the\nhardest legitimate cases. What a video is not: a passive explainer, an exploration\nsandbox, or a practice set. Independent practice belongs to the mastery quiz.\nContents\nPART 1   Constitution\n1 Authority Stack\n2 The Teaching Contract\n3 Non-Negotiables\nPART II   THE RULEBOOK\n4 How Rules Work\n5 SEQ   Direct Instruction Structure and Fidelity\n\n6 TIM   Length, Pacing, Cadence\n7 INT   Interactions\n8 LAN   Language and Tone\n9 VIS   Visuals and Multimedia\n10 GRADE   Grade Band Profiles\n11 DEV   Recorded Deviations from Stein\nPART 3   PRODUCT SPECIFICATION\n12 The Video Script Generator Tab\n13 Script Anatomy: Channels and Colors\n14 Video Skeleton\n15 Generation Pipeline  Per Lesson)\n16 QA Checklist\nPART 4   REFERENCE\n17 Translating Stein to Self-Paced Videos\n18 Where to Look in the Book\n19 Example Scripts\n20 Out of Scope and Post MVP\nPART I   CONSTITUTION\n1. Authority Stack\nEvery generation decision resolves through this stack, top down. A lower layer\nmay inform a decision only where every higher layer is silent; a lower layer may\nnever override a higher one.\nAuthority Governs\nA1 Stein, Kinder, Silbert &\nCarnine, Direct\nSupreme instructional authority: the strategy,\nits step order, wording style, sequencing,\nexample selection, error corrections. Where\n\nAuthority Governs\nInstruction Mathematics\n 5th ed., 2017 \nanything conflicts with Steinʼs method, Stein\nprevails. The only exceptions are recorded\ndeviations  DEV registry, §12  — each\nnumbered, justified, and scoped.\nA2 The lesson card\nContent authority: the single strategy to teach,\nassessment boundary, difficulty ceiling, non-\ngoals, prerequisites, objectives. The card caps\nwhat may appear; the video never teaches\npast it.\nA3 This rulebook  Part II\nregistries)\nThe delivery translation: classroom group\ninstruction →  automated, self-paced, one-\nstudent instruction. House rules for\ninteractions, pacing, language, visuals. Never\ninvents pedagogy; adapts Steinʼs to the\nmedium.\nA4 Multimedia learning\nprinciples  Mayer \nWhere A1 A3 are silent and the question is\n“how does this go on a screen”: coherence,\nsignaling, contiguity, segmenting, modality,\nredundancy, personalization, pre-training.\nTagged  MM] in the registries.\nA5\nMathematics-education\nresearch & student\npsychology\nWhere the question is representation,\nvocabulary, motivation, or age-\nappropriateness: concrete-to-abstract fading,\nsymbol grounding, variation, grade-band\nprofiles. Tagged  MathEd  /  Psych .\nConflicts are never resolved silently. When assembled inputs contradict each\nother or this stack, the run flags the lesson, proposes a default resolution derived\nfrom the stack, and waits for the user to accept or redirect (flag →  propose →\nreconcile, §13.4 . Resolutions are recorded on the script and persist.\n2. The Teaching Contract\nEvery video signs this contract. It operationalizes one sentence: teach the\nconcept so well that the student can carry it, by transfer, to the difficulty\nceiling.\n\ni. Teach the whole concept. The video gives the lesson as much as the lesson\nneeds: every step of the strategy explicitly modeled, every new term and symbol\ngrounded in plain words before use, the concept stated — not just the procedure\nperformed. Understanding is built through the taught strategy, never through\nexploration.\nii. Stop at sufficiency — the Transfer Test. Demonstration examples do NOT need\nto reach the difficulty ceiling. Examples are sufficient when: (a) every step of the\nstrategy is demonstrated on at least one example; (b) every case class the\nstrategy claims to handle appears at least once; (c) the student has performed\nevery decision type and computation type under guidance, successfully. Meet\nthat bar, and stop — the ceiling is reached through structured transfer in practice\nand the mastery quiz, and the videoʼs job is to make that transfer reasonable\n SEQ 08, SEQ 09 .\niii. Defer, donʼt drop. Harder variants excluded from the demonstration are\nscheduled downstream (later lesson or practice sets) and named in the scriptʼs\ncoverage note — never silently omitted. Never include a problem type the strategy\nas taught cannot solve  SEQ 10, SEQ 11 .\niv. Sufficiency over clock. Length is an output, not an input: as long as the lesson\nneeds, as short as sufficiency allows. No padding, no recap loops, no artificial\ncuts that break the Transfer Test. Typical lengths run 2 5 minutes by grade band\n(§11); a lesson that genuinely needs more than  6 minutes is a granularity signal —\nflag it back to the scope  TIM 01, TIM 02 .\nv. Keep the student successful. High success rate during guided steps; instant,\nspecific help; errors corrected before they are rehearsed; success is the\nmotivation engine (“Iʼm good at this. I want to keep going.”).\nvi. Stay DI. One strategy, modeled before any ask; brisk pace; frequent\nmeaningful responses; faultless wording; symbol-grounded math; mastery\nverified later by the quiz, not the video.\n3. Non-Negotiables\nThe constitutionʼs hard rules — each compiled from the registries  IDs in\nparentheses). A script violating any of these fails QA automatically and gets\nregenerated to apply the feedback.\n\ni. One lesson, one strategy — exactly the one named on the lesson card. Model\nbefore any ask; never ask what has not been taught.  SEQ 01, SEQ 02 \nii. Teach until the Transfer Test passes; stop when it does. Never cut below it;\nnever pad past it.  SEQ 08, TIM 01 \niii. Nothing beyond the card: assessment boundary and difficulty ceiling cap all\ncontent; non-goals never appear.  SEQ 14 \niv. Never more than 60 seconds without a student action; target every  30\nseconds.  TIM 04 \nv. One thought, one action per interaction. Direct production first: numeric/text\nentry whenever possible; MCQ only when the objective is truly a choice.  INT 01,\nINT 04 \nvi. Keep students successful: hint fast, never let an error be rehearsed, resume\nquickly.  INT 16 INT 18 \nvii. One canvas: full problem visible, steps persist, animate only the delta.  VIS 01 \nVIS 03 \nviii. Say it exactly when you show it — nothing early, late, or batched.  VIS 04 \nix. Active voice; no pronoun subjects; numerals, not number words (unless that is\ninvolved in the goal of the lesson); no long on-screen sentences.  LANG 03,\nLANG 04, LANG 07 \nx. Scale is exact; labels live inside diagrams; nothing decorative.  VIS 07 VIS 09 \nxi. Independent practice belongs to the mastery quiz, never the video. Released\nitems are never reproduced.  SEQ 13 \nxii. No internal vocabulary ever reaches the student.  LANG 11 \nPART II — THE RULEBOOK\nThe seven registries below are the exact text the generator receives with every\nrun. Everything is a numbered rule; nothing normative lives anywhere else in this\ndocument.\n\n4. How Rules Work\nStable IDs. Every rule has a permanent, registry-prefixed ID  SEQ 04, INT 13 .\nIDs are never renumbered and never reused — QA reports, conflict flags, and\nreconciliation records cite them, so an ID must mean the same thing forever.\nOne behavior per rule. Each rule states one enforceable behavior,\nimperatively, with an example wherever wording could be misread.\nSource tags.  Stein  the book ·  Card  the lesson card ·  House  our delivery\ntranslation ·  MM] multimedia learning principle  Mayer  ·  MathEd  math-\neducation research ·  Psych  developmental/motivational. Tags show which\nauthority a rule descends from (§2).\nOwned once. A behavior lives in exactly one registry; other registries\nreference its ID instead of restating it. Duplication is how documents drift into\ncontradiction.\n➕NOTE TO DEVELOPERS OF THE TOOL: TO ADD A RULE\n1. Pick the registry by what the rule governs: SEQ structure/DI-fidelity ·\nTIM length/pacing · INT interactions · LANG language · VIS visuals ·\nGRADE age-modulation · DEV deviation from Stein.\n2. Take the next number in that registry. Never renumber, never reuse.\n3. Write one enforceable behavior, imperative voice, example if it could\nbe misread.\n4. Tag the source   Stein p.x] ·  Card  ·  House  ·  MM  ·  MathEd  ·\n Psych  . A rule that contradicts Stein is not a rule — it is a deviation:\nrecord it in DEV with rationale and scope instead.\n5. If the new rule supersedes an old one, mark the old rule RETIRED\n(date + successor ID) in place.\n6. Add a changelog row (§22) and bump the minor version. Done — the\ngenerator picks it up on the next run.\n\n6. SEQ — Direct Instruction Structure &\nFidelity\nSEQ 01 One lesson, one strategy — exactly the strategy named on the lesson\ncard. A script that models or mentions a second computation strategy fails\nautomatically.  Stein · Card]\nSEQ 02 Model before any ask. Never ask the student about anything not yet\ntaught in this video and not named in the cardʼs Prerequisites.  Stein \nSEQ 03 The strategyʼs step order is sacred: never reorder, skip, or blend steps —\nin the model, the interactions, or the wrap.  Stein \nSEQ 04 Identical step wording every time a step occurs — within the video and\nacross videos of the same skill family. Steps stay succinct.  Stein: faultless\ncommunication]\nSEQ 05 When the book has a format for the skill, follow it: its scripted wording,\nquestion cadence, and correction scripts (adapted per §18 . When it does not, use\nthe nearest format in the skill family for rhythm only, and the chapterʼs\ninstructional procedures for content. Never borrow content across skill families. \n Stein \nSEQ 06 Preskills before strategy: Activate only prerequisite knowledge that is \ninstructionally intrinsic to the lesson's opening. A prerequisite may be retrieved\nonly if students must immediately apply that exact knowledge to understand the\nfirst model. Retrieve it only when it is the same knowledge or decision students\nuse in the first modeled example. Skip any prerequisite that would introduce a\ndifferent mathematical topic, representation, or procedure. Do not retrieve\nprerequisites that are merely listed on the card but are unrelated to the lesson's\nopening task or reasoning.  Stein · MM: pre-training]\nSEQ 07 Example selection: Select examples that are solved entirely by the\nlesson's taught strategy. Include look-alikes or non-examples only when the\nlesson objective explicitly includes discriminating when the strategy applies or\nthe card's boundaries require it. Never introduce a new selection or classification\ndecision as a secondary objective.  Stein \nSEQ 08 Problem presentation: When providing a problem to the student, display\nthe complete problem throughout instruction, keeping it visible on screen while\n\nthe solution is explained.  House \nSEQ 09 The Transfer Test (sufficiency bar): every step of the strategy\ndemonstrated on at least one example; every case class the strategy claims to\nhandle shown at least once; the student has performed every decision type and\ncomputation type under guidance, successfully. Meet the bar →  stop teaching. \n House, per Stein/explicit-teaching research]\nSEQ 10 Defer, donʼt drop: case classes excluded from the demonstration are\nscheduled downstream and listed in the scriptʼs coverage note — never silently\nomitted.  House \nSEQ 11 Never include a problem type the strategy as taught cannot solve.  Stein \nSEQ 12 Corrections follow model–test–delayed test: hint that models the fix →\nshow the step and move on →  re-check the same decision later when flow allows.\nCorrection wording comes from the formatʼs own correction script.  Stein \nSEQ 13 Independent practice never appears in the video — the mastery quiz\nowns it. Released items are never reproduced (they calibrate difficulty only); the\nscript writes parallel problems at the same demand.  House · Card]\nSEQ 14 The card is absolute: assessment boundary and difficulty ceiling cap all\ncontent; non-goals are forbidden content — never mentioned, modeled, or\ngestured at.  Card \nSEQ 15 Concept before procedure: when the lesson introduces a new rule, term,\nor notation, state it in plain words with one concrete example in the opening —\nbefore the first modeled problem. The student never meets a term for the first time\ninside a step.  House · MathEd]\nSEQ 16 Demonstrations need not reach the difficulty ceiling. The ceiling is\nreached through structured transfer in practice and the mastery quiz; the videoʼs\nobligation is to make that transfer reasonable — no case class the quiz will\ndemand may be structurally novel to the student.  House \nSEQ 17Source-page citations: Whenever Direct Instruction Mathematics is cited,\nuse the page number printed on the book page itself, never the PDF viewerʼs page\nnumber or file-page index. Verify the printed page number before citing it. When\nthe cited material spans multiple book pages, cite the exact inclusive page range.\nNever estimate, infer, or convert a book page number from its position in the PDF.\n\nEvery citation must include a hyperlink screenshot of that exact page in the\ntextbook with the text highlighted.\n7. TIM — Length, Pacing, Cadence\nTIM 01 Sufficiency over clock: the video runs as long as the lesson needs and as\nshort as sufficiency allows  SEQ 08 . Length is an output. No padding, no recap\nloops, no artificial cuts.  House \nTIM 02 Typical lengths run 2 5 minutes by grade band  GRADE table). A lesson\nthat genuinely needs more than  6 minutes to pass the Transfer Test is too big for\none video: flag for reconciliation as a granularity signal back to the scope. Never\ncompress teaching to dodge the flag.  House \nTIM 03 Title portion of the opening: ≤ 10 seconds. Use the exact title that is on the\nlesson card  House \nTIM 04 Cadence: target a student action every  30 seconds of running time;\nnever exceed 60 seconds. The only sanctioned stretch past 30 is an unbreakable\nmodeled thought.  House · MM: segmenting]\nTIM 05 Interaction count: at least 3 per video, roughly 2 3 per minute, scaled to\nlength — and never so many that the learner loses the thread.  House \nTIM 06 Pause only at clean thought boundaries — end of sentence or end of\nstep. Never mid-sentence, mid-word, or mid-animation.  House \nTIM 07 Pause choreography: cue line as a complete sentence (“Your turn — do\nthe ones.”) →  0.5 1.0s hold on the exact frame →  freeze →  prompt →  one-line\nfeedback →  resume into the next action on the same frame.  House \nTIM 08 Chunk long models: if the full model would run past  40 seconds, split it\nat numbered-step boundaries and place a check after each chunk. Never interrupt\na step.  House · MM: segmenting]\nTIM 09 When trimming is required, cut in this order: discrimination pass →\nsecond-example interaction depth →  the second example itself →  narration\ntightness. Never cut below the Transfer Test  SEQ 08 ; if the test would break,\nthat is a TIM 02 flag, not a cut.  House \n\n8. INT — Interactions\nPurpose: prevent passive watching; maximize opportunities to respond;\nstrengthen memory through retrieval; keep the DI feel (model →  guided\nparticipation) with a high success rate. Placement and cadence live in TIM;\nwording lives in LANG.\nWhen and what to ask\nINT 01 One thought, one action: one number, one decision, one click, or one drag\nper interaction. Split anything bigger into micro-steps.  House \nINT 02 Skeleton placement (§15): opening 0 1 preskill retrieval; 1 check after the\nfull model, or 1 per chunk  TIM 08 ; 2 6 micro-checks in We Do; 1 2 instant\nchecks in the discrimination pass; wrap 0 1 instant.  House \nINT 03 After a correct answer the canvas records it and the video moves on —\nnever re-teach the step the student just performed.  House \nINT 04 Direct production first: if the target skill can be demonstrated by\nproducing the answer, use numeric/text entry. MCQ is reserved for objectives that\ngenuinely are a choice or discrimination that cannot be measured more directly.\nNever use an MCQ as a worked example unless the lesson objective requires it. \n House \nINT 05 Match modality to the thinking: compute →  numeric entry · discrete\ndecision →  MCQ (per INT 04  · locate on screen →  click-to-highlight · manipulate\na representation →  simple drag.  House \nINT 06 Continuous discriminations — boundaries on a continuum (angle near 90°,\nclose lengths, slopes) — need stepped or learner-controlled interactions that\nshow gradual change. If that exceeds MVP types, flag it rather than forcing an\nMCQ; static discrete examples do not teach a perceptual boundary.  House ·\nMathEd]\nINT 07 Require retrieval or calculation. Banned: restating what is on screen, “Does\nthat make sense?”, “Did you follow the steps?”, personal-experience prompts,\nopen-ended or subjective questions.  House \nINT 08 Two-test gate for every interaction: (a) the next beat of the video\naddresses the answer; (b) producing the answer strengthens something the\nlesson must secure.  House \n\nWriting the prompt\nINT 09 Stems use on-screen context only — no new information, no untaught\nvocabulary or notation.  House \nINT 10 Name exactly what is asked, restating the on-screen question: “Ones: 8  \n7 = __”, never a bare “What is the answer?”  House \nINT 11 Signal before asking: highlight the exact region the prompt refers to  VIS \n05 . Never make the student hunt.  MM: signaling]\nResponse formats\nINT 12 Numeric entry: numeric-only, one number per prompt; math shown\nvertically with place values and decimals aligned; keypad and Submit visible\nwithout scrolling.  House \nINT 13 MCQ (when INT 04 justifies one): 3 4 concise options; distractors are\nauthentic, documented misconceptions; no mathematically equivalent options, no\n“all/none of the above,” no negatives, no tricks. Option letters typeset separately\nfrom answer text, consistently indented.  House · Stein: error patterns]\nINT 14 Read options aloud only when they are sentences or phrases; never read\nnumbers, symbols, or graphs aloud.  MM: redundancy]\nINT 15 Click-to-highlight: 2 6 predefined, generous hot zones. Simple drag:\nmarked drop zones, snap on drop, one move; no freeform drawing, no precision\nplacement.  House \nFeedback and corrections\nINT 16 Feedback within 0.5 seconds, specific, one line plus a pointer (“Look at the\nones place.”). Never a generic “Try again!”  House \nINT 17 Correct →  confirm and link to the step (“Yes — carry the 1.”), then resume\nimmediately. Never say “right” unless the answer was actually validated.  House \nINT 18 Wrong, try 1 →  smallest pinpoint hint, re-signal the region. Wrong, try 2 →\nshow the step highlighted and move on. Never stall the lesson; never let an error\nbe rehearsed.  House · Stein]\nINT 19 Correction wording and the delayed re-check follow SEQ 12.  Stein \nINT 20 Feedback stays on the frame with the math — never a separate\nexplanation screen.  MM: contiguity]\n\n9. LANG — Language & Tone\nLANG 01 Faultless communication: every sentence reads one way only. If a line\ncould be misread, rewrite it. Consistent language and symbols across the whole\nvideo and its interactions.  Stein \nLANG 02 Steps are actions the student performs: “Count the flowers: 4”, never\n“There are 4 flowers.”  House \nLANG 03 No pronouns as sentence subjects — no “it,” “they,” “this is” —\nanywhere: narration, text, prompts, feedback. Use the antecedent: “The ones\ncolumn adds to 15.”  House \nLANG 04 Numerals, not number words (“8”, not “eight”) in text, prompts, and\nfeedback — unless number words are the learning objective.  House \nLANG 05 One new term at a time: say it in plain English →  show it in action →\nrepeat it clearly in use (“We call that a factor. In 3   4, both 3 and 4 are factors. 3\nand 4 are the factors of 12.”). Never stack unfamiliar terms on one screen.\nIntroduction happens in the opening, per SEQ 15.  Stein · MathEd]\nLANG 06 Conversational, warm, brisk — talk to the learner (“you,” “we”): “Letʼs\ntry that again, together.” Students tune out mechanical, canned narration; the\nvoice is human, non-monotonous, consistent.  MM: personalization, voice]\nLANG 07 No long written sentences on screen. The screen carries numerals,\nsymbols, and short labels; the voice carries the sentences.  MM: modality]\nLANG 08 Precise math vocabulary at student level; never hide the math under\ncute theme names — the distributive property is not “detective math.”  MathEd \nLANG 09 Never teach keyword-scanning for operations in word problems; attack\nmeaning through the taught problem-solving structures.  MathEd: Powell]\nLANG 10 Read expressions as written, in symbol order: 2,352   42 reads “2,352\ndivided by 42”  DEV 01 . Inside algorithm steps, the formatʼs step wording still\napplies (“How many times does 42 go into 235?”).  House: DEV 01 \nLANG 11 Internal vocabulary never reaches the student: “start cue,” “decision\npath,” “atom,” “I Do / We Do,” “discrimination,” “interaction,” “boundary,” “ceiling.”\n\nTranslate to student terms: “When you see a division problem with a 2-digit\ndivisor, use long division: divide, multiply, subtract, bring down.”  House \nLANG 12 Praise is real, brief, and tied to the step (“Yes — 6 tens.”). No hollow\ncheer; motivation comes from earned success.  Psych \nLANG 13 Reading level, sentence length, narration pace, and tone follow the\ngrade-band profile  GRADE table). Grades 6 8 are never talked down to.  Psych \n10. VIS — Visuals & Multimedia\nVIS 01 One canvas, whole problem: show the full problem (and any options) up\nfront; keep a single clean diagram. Animate only instruction-driven actions —\nhighlighting terms, drawing helper lines, placing labels, moving terms, revealing\nintermediate calculations, simplifying.  MM: coherence]\nVIS 02 Animate the delta, keep text static: animate only when  70%+ of the\nframe is unchanged. Cut to a new still only for true layout changes. For\ncomparisons, prefer a brief ghost/overlay or split-screen over re-showing the\nscene.  House · MM \nVIS 03 Problem →  steps →  solution always visible: never hide the problem or\nintermediate steps as the solution develops. Important text, symbols, and visuals\nstay on screen while discussed — transient information is disruptive.  MM:\ntransience]\nVIS 04 Exact synchronization: every value appears at the exact moment it is\nstated — never early, late, or batched. Never introduce one number while\nexplaining another. Mark called-out intermediate unknowns with a placeholder\n(“?”).  MM: temporal contiguity]\nVIS 05 Purposeful, temporary highlighting: highlight only the elements being\ndiscussed, exactly when referenced; fade after use. Color guides attention in the\nmoment and never accumulates.  MM: signaling]\nVIS 06 Connect diagram to operations: when a step uses lengths, segments, or\nregions, visually indicate exactly which ones, at that moment. Every visual change\ncorresponds to a reasoning step; nothing appears or disappears without a reason.\n House \n\nVIS 07 Scale is sacred: anything meant to be equal is exactly equal on screen —\nticks on a number line, sides of a square, shaded fraction regions. Wrong scale\nteaches wrong perception.  MathEd \nVIS 08 Labels live inside diagrams (spatial contiguity), never in side legends. \n MM: spatial contiguity]\nVIS 09 Teaching animations only — demonstrating mathematical actions (carry\narrow, area-tile slide) or adding emphasis. No decorative images, no seductive\ndetails, no busy images.  MM: coherence]\nVIS 10 Concrete is a hook, abstract is the destination: brief concrete\nrepresentations (counters, ten frames) to connect prior knowledge, then fade to\nsymbols fast. Models and pictures are scaffolds meant to be removed.  MathEd:\nDeLoache 2000; Heckler 2006; Kaminski 2008 \nVIS 11 Symbol grounding: map every number and symbol to math words and\nlearned relationships — order, fact families, ratios, parts of a whole — the moment\nthe notation first appears.  MathEd: Reynvoet & Sasanguie 2016 \nVIS 12 Variation and non-examples: start simple, then boundary cases   0,  1 ,\nthen vary the surface while keeping the structure. Show non-examples with\nexplicit contrast: “This square is not a triangle. Squares have 4 sides; triangles\nhave 3.”  MathEd · Stein]\nVIS 13 One look and feel: Google font “Teachers” (open 4; correct numeral\nexemplars); consistent palette, instantly recognizable. Channel colors (§14) are\nreserved for scripts, not the video.  House \nVIS 14   Complete non-student-facing visual descriptions: Every visual must\ninclude a thorough production-only description enclosed in << >> . This\ndescription is metadata for reviewers, accessibility, and visual production; it is\nnever shown or read to students. The script, narration, on-screen text, prompts,\nand interactions must not refer to the description, quote it, instruct students to\nread it, or assume students have access to any information contained only within\nit.\nThe description must identify every mathematically relevant element of the visual,\nincluding the visual type, objects shown, quantities, labels, symbols, values,\nspatial arrangement, dimensions, relative scale, proportions, spacing, color\ncoding, grouping, alignment, direction, sequence, and any changes across\n\nframes. Describe only what is actually visible at that moment, and explicitly state\nwhen mathematically relevant labels, symbols, values, or annotations are not\nshown. Specify the size and placement of each element using measurable\nconstraints whenever they affect meaning or reproducibility. Use exact pixel\ndimensions and coordinates when the canvas size is fixed; otherwise, use\nproportions or explicit ratios, such as “the title is 4 times the height of the diagram\nlabels,” “the number line occupies 80% of the canvas width,” or “each tick interval\nis equal and measures one-sixth of the line.” Do not use vague terms such as\n“large,” “small,” “near,” “centered approximately,” or “well spaced” without a\nmeasurable definition.\nThe description must also state both what must appear and what must not appear,\nincluding any prohibited objects, labels, symbols, colors, annotations, groupings,\nmovements, or visual relationships that could alter the mathematical meaning. It\nmust explain the mathematical relationship or instructional purpose represented\nby the visual. Include enough detail, including explicit inclusion and exclusion\nconstraints, for a reviewer or visual producer to recreate the visual consistently\nand precisely across repeated generations. Decorative details may be omitted\nonly when they do not affect mathematical meaning, interpretation, or\nreproducibility.\nWhen multiple text or visual elements appear, define their size hierarchy explicitly.\nState the relative size of titles, mathematical expressions, labels, annotations, and\ndecorative elements rather than merely describing one as larger or smaller.\nA visual fails this requirement if:\n   any mathematically relevant information is missing from the << >>  description;\n   the description does not specify both what must appear and what must not\nappear when either is necessary to prevent ambiguity or variation;\n   the description permits materially different visual interpretations,\narrangements, labels, symbols, groupings, colors, sequences, or mathematical\nrelationships across repeated recreations;\n   the student-facing lesson refers to, quotes, or depends on the description; or\n   information necessary for the student is present only in the description rather\nthan in the narration, on-screen content, or interaction itself.\n\n11. GRADE — Grade-Band Profiles\nThe DI skeleton never changes with grade; the profile modulates length, language,\nreading load, interaction mix, and tone. Two invariants never modulate: high\nsuccess rate and the cadence band  TIM 04 . Values are defaults to tune with\nstudent data.  Current corpora run grades 3 8; K 2 is specified for\ncompleteness.)\nK 1 2 3 4 5 6 8\nTypical length 1 00 2 30 2 00 3 30 2 30 4 30 3 00 5 00\nNarration pace\n 110 125 wpm;\nlong response\npauses\n 125 140 wpm  140 155 wpm  150 165 wpm\nSentences ≤ 8 words, one\nclause\nShort; one idea\neach\nShort; two\nclauses max Natural but tight\nOn-screen\nreading aside\nfrom the\nproblem text\nNumerals +\nsingle words;\nnarrator reads\nevery screen\nword aloud\nNumerals +\nshort phrases;\nprompts read\naloud\nShort step\nlabels persist;\nsentence\nprompts read\naloud\nStep labels +\nsymbolic work;\nread-aloud per\nINT 14\nPsychology notes per band\nK 1. Working memory holds one to two novel elements; every extra on-screen\nobject is load. Audio carries the lesson; the screen shows only what is being\ndiscussed. Success must be near-certain — a five-year-old who misses twice\ndisengages — so hints arrive instantly and drags snap generously. Routine is a\nfeature: identical cues, identical panel, identical voice.\n2 3. Fact retrieval is the fluency frontier: brisk numeric checks build\nautomaticity, but timed pressure stays out of the video (fluency rates belong to\nthe app). Students this age rehearse errors quickly — the two-try ladder and\nimmediate correction matter most here. Tie steps to place-value meaning\nwhile keeping step wording identical every time.\n\n4 5. Solution chains lengthen (multi-digit algorithms, fractions), so\npersistence of intermediate steps on screen is the main load-management\ntool. Vocabulary precision (numerator, denominator, quotient) is taught one\nterm at a time. Motivation shifts to competence: name what the student just\ndid (“You renamed the ten — that was the hard part.”).\n6 8. Adolescents disengage at the first hint of being talked down to: praise\ngets rarer and more specific, tone stays adult, examples stay purposeful.\nErrors are information, never verdicts; recovery is fast and private — a solo\nlearnerʼs advantage, use it. Abstraction is the default; concrete models appear\nonly to ground a genuinely new structure and fade within the video. Symbol\ngrounding still rules.\n12. DEV — Recorded Deviations from Stein\nStein prevails over everything (§2). The only sanctioned exceptions are the entries\nbelow — each numbered, justified, and scoped. A proposed rule that contradicts\nStein belongs here, or nowhere. Conflict handling (§13.4) treats DEV entries as\nsettled house style and does not flag them.\nNone exist so far. Through QCing, if any appear, they will be added to this table\nwith what Stein says, what we do instead, why, and exactly where the deviation\napplies.\nID Deviation Justification & scope\nDEV 01\nDEV 02 \nPART III — PRODUCT SPECIFICATION\n13. The Video Script Generator Tab\n13.1 Placement and flow\n\nNavigation: top-level tab “Video Script Generator”, immediately after “Lesson\nScope Edits”.\nStep 1 — pick a course: generated courses from the course registry (name,\nsubject, grade, standard set, active-lesson count). Active lessons only.\nStep 2 — pick lessons: multi-select grouped by unit in lesson order (chip-\ntoggle pattern from Lesson Scope Edits), select-all-per-unit, optional free-text\nsteering instruction.\nStep 3 — generate: one run per request, per-lesson progress, slim runs list.\nEach finished script opens in a viewer rendering the channel colors (§14), with\nper-lesson regenerate.\n13.2 Inputs assembled per lesson\nInput Content\nLesson card\nAll card fields: lesson title, unit, standard ID, lesson order, objectives, new\nlearning (start cue · single decision path · response form), instructional\napproach, prerequisites, progression placement, assessment boundary,\ndifficulty ceiling, non-goals, assessment evidence, released items.\nCourse contextSubject, grade, standard set — grade selects the GRADE profile.\nDoctrine  Stein  Prioritize alignment with the textbook whenever its instructional format,\nwording, example sequence, and correction procedures can be faithfully\ntranslated to self-paced multimedia. Depart from the textbook only when\na direct translation would conflict with the lesson card, the rulebook, the\ncapabilities of the medium, or the needs of an individual self-paced\nlearner; any departure must preserve the instructional purpose of the\noriginal method\nExcerpts retrieved for the lessonʼs skill family: the matching format(s) with\nscripted wording, chapter procedures, correction scripts, error patterns\n— located via the book index (§19), the textbook, and the DI Knowledge\nGraph page mapping. Each has a hyperlink to a screenshot of the cited\npage.\nWhen a textbook script is reproduced, adapted, or materially influences\nthe generated video script, the source must be cited explicitly. This\nrequirement applies even when the original classroom script has been\n\nInput Content\nmodified for self-paced multimedia delivery, such as replacing teacher\nsignals, group responses, board work, or correction routines with\nnarration, animation, and checked interactions. The citation must identify\nthe exact printed book page and link to the corresponding page\nscreenshot.\nThis rulebook\nPart I verbatim + all Part II registries verbatim + the skeleton (§15).\nVersioned; every script records the rulebook version it ran under. This is\nversion is version 7.14\n13.3 Output\nOne Video Script per lesson: timed segments of channel-tagged lines (§14) with\nfully specified interactions, plus a coverage note — the machine-readable list of\ncase classes taught vs. deferred  SEQ 10  — and any recorded reconciliations.\nStored per (course, lesson) with a version; stamped with rulebook and doctrine\nversions; exportable (.docx/.pdf). The script is a production contract: precise\nenough for downstream audio, animation, and player systems to execute without\ninterpretation.\n13.4 Conflict handling: flag →  propose →  reconcile\nGeneration never silently resolves a contradiction. When assembled inputs\nconflict — card-internal (approach vs. non-goals; objectives beyond boundary),\ncard vs. Stein, card vs. rulebook  Transfer Test cannot fit sanity limits; needed\ninteraction type beyond MVP; production exceeds grade profile), or steering vs.\nany of the above — the run pauses for that lesson only:\n1. Flag. Status becomes “needs reconciliation”; the flag names both sides, cites\nthe exact fields, doctrine pages, and rule IDs, and states in one line why\ngeneration cannot proceed cleanly.\n2. Propose. A default resolution is always offered, with a one-line rationale\nderived from the authority stack (§2). The user never faces a blank decision.\n3. Reconcile. The user accepts the default in one click or types their own\nhandling. The lesson generates only after the choice.\n\n4. Record. The resolution is written into the script header (both sides, rule IDs\napplied, resolution, who resolved) and persists per (lesson, conflict);\nregenerations pre-fill it; a card edit that changes either side re-opens the flag.\nGuardrail: a user resolution may relax house defaults (timing, interaction counts)\nbut can never cross the cardʼs boundary or non-goals  SEQ 14 , never break the\nTransfer Test  SEQ 08 , and never introduces a second strategy  SEQ 01 .\n13.5 Engineering notes (planning level)\nOne generation call per lesson, checkpointed per lesson through the existing\nqueue-worker pattern  10-minute budget; failed runs resume; batched\nparallelism).\nStructured-generation service with a shared-$defs JSON schema: script →\nsegments →  lines { channel, content, timing }, interactions as first-class\nobjects { type, prompt, options/answer, feedback ladder, resume state, model-\naccess flag }, plus coverage note and reconciliation records.\nDoctrine retrieval is page-targeted (book index + knowledge graph), never\nwhole-book context.\nThe tab does not render video, generate audio/image assets, or author the\nquiz — the script is the contract those systems consume.\n14. Script Anatomy: Channels & Colors\nEvery script line carries exactly one channel; the channel owns its color in the\nviewer and exports. A line never mixes channels; simultaneity is expressed by\nadjacent lines sharing a timestamp.\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nNarration  SAY  Black The verbatim\nspoken script,\nword-for-word\nas the voice\ndelivers it:\nmodel wording\nand step\nEvery word the\nnarrator speaks\n(rules: LANG\nregistry; pace per\nGRADE .\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nlanguage,\nidentical at\nevery\noccurrence;\nspoken counting\nsequences (\"1,\n2, 3\"); plain-\nwords\nintroductions of\nnew terms and\nnotation; the cue\nsentence that\nprecedes every\nfreeze;\nexpressions\nread in symbol\norder;\ntransitions and\nthe one-line\nwrap summary.\nComplete\nsentences only,\nending at clean\nthought\nboundaries;\nactive voice, no\npronoun\nsubjects, no\ninternal\nvocabulary;\nsentence length\nand pace per\nGRADE.\nExcludes:\ninteraction\nprompts and\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nfeedback (those\nlive inside the\nINTERACTION\nobject), visual\ndirections, on-\nscreen strings,\ntiming marks.\nOn-screen text TEXT  Blue The literal\ncharacters\nrendered on the\ncanvas, exactly\nas typeset:\nnumerals and\nmath symbols\n(\"4   3\", \"__\"\nplaceholders) ·\nshort labels and\nstep records\n(\"Groups: 3\", \"In\neach: 2\") · the\nlesson title ·\nrule-card labels\n· equation\nframes and their\nfills · persistent\nanswer-strip\nand worked-\nstep writes  VIS \n03 . Every string\nis anchored to\nthe exact\nspoken moment\nit appears  VIS \n04) and may\ncarry a << >>\nplacement/sync\nspec. Numerals,\nnever number\nwords unless\nWords and\nnumerals\nrendered on the\ncanvas —\nnumerals and\nshort labels only,\nstatic,\nsynchronized\n LANG 07, VIS \n04 .\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nthe objective\ninvolves it\n LANG 04 ;\nlabels and short\nphrases, never\nsentences\n LANG 07 ;\nstatic once\nplaced  VIS 02 .\nExcludes: long\nwritten\nsentences, text\nthe narration\nnever grounds,\ndecorative text,\ninternal\nvocabulary\n LANG 11 .\nVisual  VISUAL  Green Every display,\nanimation, and\nhighlight\ninstruction:\ncanvas layout\nand scene setup\n· the animated\ndelta — what\nmoves, morphs,\nglides, fades,\nand what stays\nstatic  VIS 02  ·\nhighlight targets\nand their fade\n VIS 05  ·\ndiagram-internal\nlabels  VIS 08  ·\nexact-scale\nrequirements\n VIS 07  ·\npersistence and\nImages,\ndiagrams,\nanimation\ndirections,\nhighlights  VIS\nregistry).\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nreset behavior\nof problems,\nsteps, and\nreference cards\n VIS 03  · sync\nanchors naming\nthe spoken word\neach visual\nevent lands on\n VIS 04  · and,\nmandatory on\nevery visual, the\n<< >>\nproduction\ndescription\n VIS 14   visual\ntype, objects,\nquantities,\nlabels, symbols,\nvalues, spatial\narrangement,\nrelative size,\ncolor coding,\ngrouping,\nalignment,\ndirection,\nsequence,\nchanges across\nframes, plus the\nmathematical\nrelationship or\ninstructional\npurpose —\ncomplete\nenough for a\nproducer to\nreconstruct the\nvisual.\nExcludes:\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nspoken words,\ndecorative\nelements  VIS \n09 , and any\nstudent-\nnecessary\ninformation\npresent only\ninside the << >>\ndescription\n VIS 14 failure\ncondition).\nInteraction  INTERACTION Purple The complete\nfirst-class\ninteraction\nobject — all 8\nfields, none\noptional: type\n(numeric entry ·\nMCQ · click-to-\nhighlight ·\nsimple drag;\nmodality\nmatches the\nthinking, INT 05 \n· prompt —\nexact wording\nrestating the on-\nscreen question\n INT 10 , on-\nscreen-context\nlanguage only\n INT 09  ·\noptions /\naccepted\nanswer / zones\n— MCQ  3 4\noptions,\nmisconception\nA checked\ninteraction, fully\nspecified  INT\nregistry): type ·\nprompt ·\noptions/accepted\nanswer · correct\nfeedback · try-1\nhint · try-2 show-\nand-resume ·\nresume state ·\nmodel-access\nflag.\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\ndistractors,\nletters typeset\nseparately  INT \n13 ; numeric:\none accepted\nnumber  INT \n12 ; click: 2 6\ngenerous zones;\ndrag: marked\nsnap zones, one\nmove  INT 15  ·\ncorrect\nfeedback — one\nline, tied to the\nstep  INT 17,\nLANG 12  · try-1\nhint — smallest\npinpoint hint +\nre-signaled\nregion  INT 18  ·\ntry-2 show-\nand-resume —\nshow the step\nhighlighted,\nmove on;\ncorrection\nwording from\nthe format's\nscript  INT 18,\nSEQ 12  ·\nresume state —\nexact frame and\nnext action  INT \n23  · model-\naccess flag —\nthe \"Show\nmodel\" replay\ntarget, or none\nfor lesson-\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\nindependent\nchecks  INT 24 .\nPlus signal-\nbefore-ask  INT \n11 , UI\nplacement — rail\n/ tray / on-\ncanvas  INT 21,\nINT 22  — and\noption read-\naloud behavior\n INT 14 .\nExcludes:\nbanned stems\n INT 07 ,\nuntaught\nvocabulary,\ngeneric \"Try\nagain!\"  INT 16 .\nProduction\nnote\n NOTE  Gray italic Production and\nQA metadata\nonly: timing\nmarks and\nsegment stamps\n· freeze/hold\nchoreography\nbeats  TIM 07  ·\nrule-ID citations\njustifying every\nnon-obvious\ndecision ·\nrationales for\nskipped\nelements\n(\"preskill check\nskipped — firm\nper card, SEQ \n06\") ·\ndesignated TIM \nTiming marks,\nfreeze frames,\nasset and voice\nnotes, rule-ID\ncitations. Never\nteaching content.\n\nChannel Tag Color Contains Carries\n09 trim points ·\ncoverage-note\nand Transfer\nTest attestations\n· cadence and\nlength math ·\nasset, voice-\ndirection, and\ntone notes ·\nreconciliation\nreferences\n(§13.4). Written\nfor producers,\nreviewers, and\nQA. Excludes,\nabsolutely:\nteaching\ncontent,\nanything spoken\nor shown to the\nstudent,\nstudent-facing\nlanguage of any\nkind.\nNotes:\n[SAY]  must capture the exact spoken wording, while the interaction prompt\ncaptures what the student sees and may not use the same wording. For\nexample, the prompt may display 4.05 , but [SAY]  should specify whether it is\nread as “4 and 5 hundredths” or “4 point zero five.”\nIf text appears within a visual, note it in a visual tag: [VISUAL]\nHowever, if text appears on the screen outside of a visual, note it in a text tag: \n[TEXT]\nIn every  [VISUAL]  line, describe only what is actually visible on screen at that\nmoment. Do not name, imply, or annotate mathematical values, labels,\nanswers, or interpretations unless they are explicitly shown in the visual at that\ntime. If a mathematically relevant identity is not yet displayed, either omit it\n\nfrom the  [VISUAL] line or state explicitly that it is not shown. Use  [NOTE]  for\nproducer-only interpretation when needed.\nExample: Write, “point P at the fifth tick; no fraction label is shown yet,” not,\n“point labeled P at the fifth tick  5/6 ” unless “5/6” is visibly printed on the\nscreen.\n15. Video Skeleton\nBudgets are typical, not caps — sufficiency governs  TIM 01, TIM 02 . Segment\nnames are internal; students never hear them  LANG 11 .\nSegment Typical Purpose Interactions\nOpening 0 15 0 45\nTitle ( ≤ 10s, TIM 03   name the\nskill in student terms; concisely\nset the goal. If the card lists\nfragile prerequisites: one quick\nretrieval check  SEQ 06 . Then, if\nthe lesson introduces a new rule,\nterm, or notation: state it in plain\nwords with one concrete example\nbefore the first problem  SEQ 15,\nLANG 05, VIS 10 . Then, i\n0 1 (intro and\npreskill retrieval,\nif applicable).\nI Do 0 45 2 00\nModel the complete routine,\nfaultless wording, per the formatʼs\nstructured presentation (§18).\nEvery step visible and\nsynchronized. Chunk models\nrunning past  40s at step\nboundaries  TIM 08 .\n1 after a short\nmodel; 1 per\nchunk of a\nchunked model.\nWe Do 1 00 2 30 Second example as guided micro-\nsteps: the formatʼs question\nsequence becomes the\ninteraction chain. The student\nperforms every calculation and\ndecision before the canvas\nrecords it. Add further guided\nexamples only while the Transfer\n2 6 per example\n(one step or\ncalculation each).\n\nSegment Typical Purpose Interactions\nTest  SEQ 08) still has unmet\ncase classes.\nDiscrimination\npass (optional) 0 20 0 45\nMixed look-alikes from the\nformatʼs Part C (regroup vs. no-\nregroup) when the boundary\nallows — the “when do I use it”\ncheck, never a new worked\nexample  SEQ 07 .\n1 2 instant\nchecks.\nWrap 0 10 0 20 Conclude the lesson with a concise\none-line summary of the strategy,\nrule, or key idea. Never bridge to\nthe mastery quiz or name what\ncomes next.\n0 1, only if truly\ninstant.\nNOTE  If additional I DO/WE DO problems are needed in order to fully cover\nvariations within the lesson, include them as needed before the Wrap.\nAssembly logic: build until the Transfer Test passes, then stop  SEQ 08 ; trim per\nTIM 09 if flow drags; flag per TIM 02 if the atom cannot be taught in  6 minutes.\nEvery case class the quiz will demand is either taught here or named as deferred\nin the coverage note  SEQ 09, SEQ 10 .\nFormatting of the Script:\nFormat every generated script as a sequence of numbered slides. Each slide\nrepresents one stable learner-facing canvas with one clear instructional focus.\nSlide formatting must support production, reduce split attention, and preserve the\none-canvas and information-persistence requirements in VIS 01 through VIS 03. \nRequired slide format\nBegin every slide with the following header:\nSLIDE [two-digit number]: [student-facing slide title]\nTime: [start time–end time]\nSlide type: [Opening | Concept | Example | Practice | Wrap]\nCanvas: [NEW | CONTINUES FROM SLIDE ##]\nThe slide number, time, slide type, and canvas status are production metadata and\nare never shown or spoken to the student.\nThe text following SLIDE ##:  is the exact student-facing title. Include the same title\nin a [TEXT]  line at the beginning of the slide. Do not place any production-only\ninformation inside the student-facing title.\nWithin each slide, place [SAY] , [TEXT] , [VISUAL] , [INTERACTION] , and [NOTE]  lines in\n\nexact chronological order.\nSlide-title types\nEvery slide title must identify both the instructional role of the slide and the\nspecific mathematics being taught or applied. Use only the following title patterns.\nOpening\nThe opening slide uses the exact lesson title from the lesson card.\nSLIDE 01: Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nSlide type: Opening\nDo not add labels such as Introduction, Lesson Goal, or Todayʼs Lesson unless\nthose words are part of the official lesson title.\nConcept\nUse a Concept slide when introducing, defining, representing, or explaining a new\nmathematical concept, rule, term, notation, or relationship before applying it in a\ncomplete problem.\nFormat:\nConcept: [specific mathematical concept]\nExamples:\nConcept: Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nConcept: Which Ten Is Closer?\nConcept: What the Remainder Means\nConcept: Regrouping 10 Ones as 1 Ten\nConcept: Equivalent Fractions\nConcept: Area Measures the Space Inside\nThe title must describe the actual mathematical idea established on that slide. Do\nnot use generic titles such as:\nConcept Introduction\nNew Concept\nLearn the Rule\nGetting Started\nWhen a concept requires more than one slide, give each slide a title that identifies\nits specific conceptual focus.\nExample:\nConcept: The Tens Around a Number\nConcept: Which Ten Is Closer?\nExample\nUse an Example slide when the narrator models how to apply the taught concept\nor strategy. The student observes the complete model and may complete only a\nbrief confirmation check after the modeled reasoning has been taught.\nFormat:\nExample of [specific mathematical skill]\n\nExamples:\nExample of Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nExample of Regrouping the Ones\nExample of Dividing with a Remainder\nExample of Comparing Fractions\nExample of Finding the Area of a Rectangle\nExample of Choosing the Correct Operation\nThe title must describe the mathematical action or decision being modeled. If\nthere are more than one example, the title should be able to differentiate how one\nis different than the other. No two titles should be the same. \nDo not use generic or item-specific titles such as:\nExample 1\nTeacher Example\nWatch Me\nMy Turn\nExample of 47\nPractice\nUse a Practice slide when the student applies the previously modeled concept,\nstrategy, or step through guided, checked interactions.\nFormat:\nPractice [specific mathematical skill]\nExamples:\nPractice Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nPractice Regrouping the Ones\nPractice Dividing with a Remainder\nPractice Comparing Fractions\nPractice Finding the Area of a Rectangle\nPractice Choosing the Correct Operation\nA Practice slide always represents guided participation with immediate validation,\nhints, correction, and continuation. It does not represent independent practice.\nIndependent practice and mastery testing remain in the mastery quiz under SEQ \n13.\nDo not use generic titles such as:\nYour Turn\nWe Do\nTry One\nLet’s Practice\nPractice 1\nNow You Try\nMatched Example–Practice pairs\nEvery Practice slide must match a preceding Example slide. The paired titles must\n\nuse parallel wording so the student can immediately recognize that the practice\napplies the same learning demonstrated in the example.\nFor a matched pair:\n• the Example title begins with Example of ;\n• the Practice title begins with Practice ; and\n• all remaining words must match exactly.\nCorrect:\nExample of Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nPractice Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nExample of Regrouping the Ones\nPractice Regrouping the Ones\nExample of Comparing Fractions with the Same Denominator\nPractice Comparing Fractions with the Same Denominator\nIncorrect:\nExample of Rounding to the Nearest Ten\nPractice Another Rounding Problem\nExample of Regrouping the Ones\nPractice Addition\nExample of Comparing Fractions\nYour Turn\nThe pair must match in mathematical action, strategy, vocabulary, case class, and\nlevel of specificity.\nWhen the mathematical variation changes, begin a new matched pair and name\nthe variation explicitly.\nExample:\nExample of Rounding When the Ones Digit Is Less Than 5\nPractice Rounding When the Ones Digit Is Less Than 5\nExample of Rounding When the Ones Digit Is 5 or More\nPractice Rounding When the Ones Digit Is 5 or More\nDo not use one broad title for an example and a narrower or different title for its\npractice.\nSlide boundaries\nCreate a new slide only when at least one of the following occurs:\n1. the lesson shifts to a new concept, example, practice problem, decision, or\nmajor strategy step;\n2. the mathematical focus changes enough to require a new title;\n3. the visual layout must change substantially;\n\n4. a completed problem gives way to a new problem;\n5. the lesson moves from a modeled example to its matched guided practice; or\n6. the current slide would otherwise contain competing visual focal points.\nDo not create a new slide for every sentence, calculation, highlight, animation, or\ninteraction.\nNever place a slide boundary:\n• in the middle of a sentence;\n• in the middle of a strategy step;\n• between an interaction and its feedback;\n• between an incorrect response and its correction;\n• while the student must compare information across the boundary; or\n• solely to create visual variety.\nA slide change must reflect a meaningful instructional or layout change, not a\ncosmetic transition.\nCanvas continuity\nA new slide does not automatically require a new learner-facing canvas.\nUse:\nCanvas: CONTINUES FROM SLIDE ##\nwhen the problem, diagram, or mathematical workspace must remain visible\nacross slides.\nWhen the canvas continues:\n• retain the complete problem;\n• retain all previously completed work needed for the current reasoning;\n• preserve the location, size, scale, spacing, and alignment of unchanged\nelements;\n• animate only the new instructional delta;\n• do not erase and redraw unchanged work;\n• do not move mathematical elements merely to make the slide appear different;\nand\n• state explicitly in the [VISUAL]  description which elements persist unchanged.\nUse:\nCanvas: NEW\nwhen introducing a new problem, representation, or layout that does not depend\n\non the previous canvas.\nInteractions within slides\nKeep each interaction on the same slide as:\n• the complete problem or visual needed to answer it;\n• the highlighted region or signal directing attention;\n• the response control;\n• the correct feedback;\n• the try-1 hint;\n• the try-2 show-and-resume correction; and\n• the resumed mathematical work.\nDo not create separate question, correct-answer, or try-again slides.\nWhen a keypad, answer field, option tray, or response zone appears, treat it as a\ntemporary addition to the existing slide. After validation, remove or collapse the\nresponse control without clearing the mathematical work.\nThe Practice slide title remains visible throughout the interaction unless it\ncompetes with the mathematical workspace. The title must not replace the\ninteraction prompt. The prompt must still name the exact mathematical action\nrequired under INT 10.\nWrap\nCreate a separate Wrap slide. \nAlways use, “Summary  ” as the title of the Wrap Slide.\nA Wrap slide contains no new strategy, case class, or independent practice. The\nWrap concludes the lesson with a concise one-line summary of the strategy, rule,\nor key idea taught — never a bridge or forward reference to the mastery quiz.\n16. Generation Pipeline (Per Lesson)\n1. Assemble context: lesson card + course grade →  GRADE profile; load Part I \nII verbatim. Detect input conflicts and route to reconciliation (§13.4) before\ndrafting.\n2. Retrieve doctrine: locate the format(s) for the skill family (§19 + knowledge-\ngraph pages); pull scripted wording, step order, correction scripts, preskill lists,\nexample-selection guidance, documented error patterns.\n\n3. Enumerate case classes the strategy claims within the cardʼs boundary;\nmark which the video will teach and which defer downstream — this drives the\nTransfer Test and the coverage note  SEQ 08 SEQ 11 .\n4. Plan examples: first example mid-difficulty and unambiguous; further\nexamples chosen to cover remaining case classes; discrimination examples\nwhere the boundary allows  SEQ 07 . Released items calibrate demand, never\nappear  SEQ 13 .\n5. Draft the opening  SEQ 15, SEQ 06   concept/term plain-words-first with one\nconcrete hook that fades  VIS 10 ; optional preskill retrieval.\n6. Draft I Do from the formatʼs Part A per the translation map (§18); choreograph\nthe canvas  VIS registry); chunk per TIM 08.\n7. Build We Do: convert the formatʼs Part B/C question sequence into micro-\ninteractions  INT registry); write full feedback ladders with the formatʼs\ncorrection wording; set resume states; add the discrimination pass when SEQ \n07 allows.\n8. Write the wrap: conclude the lesson with a concise one-line summary of the\nstrategy, rule, or key idea; never bridge to the mastery quiz.\n9. Language pass  LANG , visual pass  VIS , then tag every line with exactly\none channel and estimate timing from the GRADE words-per-minute.\n10. Self-QC against §17 citing rule IDs; emit the script + coverage note +\nversion stamps.\n16.1 How the card fields drive the script\nCard field Consumption\nLesson title / substandard Title wording in student terms; the video teaches exactly this\nbehavior — no more.\nNew learning (start cue ·\ndecision path · response\nform)\nThe modeled routine. The start cue is stated in student terms\n(“When you see…”, LANG 11 ; the response form shapes what\ninteractions ask students to produce.\nResponse forms split by ownership: production\nforms (numeric entry, fraction/text entry, click-to-highlight,\nsimple drag) shape what video interactions ask students to\nproduce; selection forms (choice sets / MCQ) are quiz-owned\n\nCard field Consumption\n— route them to the mastery-quiz generator and record them\nin the coverage note as quiz-deferred  SEQ 10 . Selection\nlanguage on the card is never consumed as a video\ninteraction. The exception would be if the lesson requires that\nstudents choose from statements and there is no way to make\nthe examples and practice production forms.\nInstructional approach\nThe single strategy  SEQ 01) and the modeled cases →  the\nexample plan (step 4). A modeled case whose only novelty is\na selection format (a choice set) is re-cast as a production-\nform example on the same problem, or deferred to the quiz\nwith a coverage-note entry. Extension cases go to\npractice/quiz.\nObjectives / assessment\nevidence\nWhat interactions must check: each production behavior\nmaps to at least one retrieval moment where feasible, modality\nper INT 05. Selection behaviors ('select from choices,'\ndistractor discrimination) map to the mastery quiz, never to\nvideo interactions; the coverage note records them as quiz-\ndeferred  SEQ 10 \nPrerequisites Opening activation  SEQ 06) and the ceiling on what may be\nassumed  SEQ 02 .\nAssessment boundary /\ndifficulty ceiling\nThe example-difficulty window and the transfer target: teach\nso the ceiling is reachable by transfer  SEQ 09, SEQ 14 .\nNon-goals Forbidden content  SEQ 14 . QC scans for drift.\nReleased items Demand calibration only; never reproduced  SEQ 13 .\nProgression placement Optional one-line framing (“You already know how to add the\nones.”) — minimal.\n17. QA Checklist\nEvery check cites rule IDs. [hard fail] blocks the script; the rest are review flags.\nPrior to delivering, review the checklist and make any necessary edits to delivery a\nscript that passes.\nContract & structure\n\nTransfer Test passes: all steps demonstrated; all claimed case classes shown;\nevery decision/computation type performed by the student  SEQ 08  [hard\nfail]. Coverage note lists every deferred case class  SEQ 10  [hard fail].\nNo content beyond boundary/ceiling; non-goals absent  SEQ 14  [hard fail].\nReleased items not reproduced  SEQ 13  [hard fail].\nLength within the grade-band typical or justified by the Transfer Test; >  6 00\nflagged as granularity, not compressed  TIM 01, TIM 02 .\nDI fidelity\nExactly one strategy  SEQ 01  [hard fail]. Step order intact  SEQ 03  [hard\nfail]. Step wording identical across occurrences  SEQ 04  [hard fail].\nModel precedes every ask  SEQ 02  [hard fail]. New terms introduced before\nuse, plain-words-first  SEQ 15, LANG 05  [hard fail].\nExample set: solvable-only, introductory + discrimination where boundary\nallows  SEQ 07, SEQ 11 . Corrections follow SEQ 12 with format wording [hard\nfail on generic “Try again!”].\nInteractions\nCadence: ≤ 60s max gap,  30s target  TIM 04  [hard fail]; count per TIM 05;\nplacement per INT 02; choreography per TIM 06 TIM 07 [hard fail].\nOne thought one action  INT 01 ; direct production preferred, every MCQ\njustified by the objective  INT 04  [hard fail]; modality matches thinking  INT \n05 .\nStems on-screen-context only  INT 09 ; no banned question types  INT 07 \n[hard fail]; two-test gate passed  INT 08 .\nLadders complete: correct + try-1 + try-2 + resume state on every interaction\n INT 16 INT 18, INT 23  [hard fail]. “Show model” on every lesson-dependent\ncheck  INT 24 . No blocking modals  INT 21  [hard fail].\nLanguage & visuals\nNo pronoun subjects; numerals; no long on-screen sentences  LANG 03,\nLANG 04, LANG 07  [hard fail]. No internal vocabulary  LANG 11  [hard fail].\n\nExpressions read in symbol order  LANG 10 .\nOne canvas; steps persist to the end  VIS 01 VIS 03  [hard fail]. Values\nappear exactly when spoken  VIS 04  [hard fail]. Highlights fade  VIS 05 ;\nscale exact  VIS 07 ; labels in diagrams  VIS 08 ; nothing decorative  VIS 09 .\nFinal gate — three questions: Does the student have to think at the key steps, or\ncan they coast? Do the checks prevent error rehearsal and keep success high?\nDoes each interactionʼs modality match the thinking?\nPART IV — REFERENCE\n18. Translating Stein to Self-Paced Video\nThe bookʼs teaching formats are two-column scripts — TEACHER wording,\nexpected STUDENT responses — in numbered steps, typically four parts. The four\nparts are a gradual release of responsibility and map directly onto the skeleton\n(§15):\nStein format part Video equivalent\nPart A — structured\nboard presentation\nI Do: narrated one-canvas model; teacher wording adapted nearly\nverbatim; the board becomes the animated canvas; confirm-check\nafter the model.\nPart B — structured\nworksheet\nWe Do: the formatʼs question sequence becomes the micro-\ninteraction chain — each teacher question that expected a student\nanswer becomes one interaction (direct production first, INT 04 .\nPart C — less\nstructured worksheet\nDiscrimination pass / late We Do: mixed look-alike checks  SEQ \n07 .\nPart D — supervised\npractice;\nindependent\nworksheets\nMastery quiz. Out of video scope  SEQ 13 .\n18.1 Teacher-move translation map\n\nClassroom move  Stein  Video translation\nSignal: hand drop, clap,\ntouch, point-and-pause\nCue sentence →  0.5 1.0s hold →  freeze →  prompt  TIM 07 .\nThe same cue pattern every time, so the student always\nknows an answer is expected.\nUnison oral response\nA checked interaction  INT registry). Every student answers\nevery check — stronger than a choral response, where\nindividuals can hide.\n“My turn” / “Your turn”\nframing\nKeep the pairing of Model vs. participation. Use “example” for\n“my turn” and “practice” for “your turn.”\nModel–Lead–Test\nModel = I Do. Lead = We Do guided steps with instant hints.\nTest = the same step re-asked without help in flow; the full test\nis the quiz.\nError correction: model–\ntest–delayed test\nThe feedback ladder  INT 16 INT 19) with the formatʼs\ncorrection wording; the delayed test is a later re-check of the\nsame decision  SEQ 12 .\n“Repeat until firm”\nThe video keeps flow (max two tries per check); the quiz owns\nfirmness. “Show model” replaces re-presentation  INT 24  —\nnever punish non-listening with guessing.\nIndividual turns Unnecessary — the interaction layer gives every student an\nindividual turn on every check.\nMonitoring written work\n(“Check.”) Automatic validation; wrong work never accumulates  INT 18 .\nTeacher writes on board\nstep by step\nThe canvas animates exactly the written delta at the moment it\nis narrated  VIS 02, VIS 04 ; problem, steps, and answer stay\nvisible  VIS 03 .\n18.2 Interaction type reference\nType Use when Constraints & ladder\nNumeric entry\nThe student produces a\ncomputed sub-result: ones sum,\ncarry digit, missing factor, side\nlength. The default  INT 04 .\nOne number; vertical alignment;\nkeypad + Submit visible  INT 12 .\nLadder: “Yes — 15.” / hint / show\nstep + resume  INT 16 INT 18 .\nMCQ The objective truly is a choice or\ndiscrimination: “Do we regroup?”,\n3 4 options; misconception\ndistractors; letters separate from\n\nType Use when Constraints & ladder\n“Area or perimeter?”, “Which\nequation matches?”  INT 04 .\ntext  INT 13 ; read-aloud per INT \n14.\nClick-to-highlight\nIdentify something on screen:\nthe tens digit, the measured side,\nthe numerator, the next column.\n2 6 generous zones; signal first\n INT 11, INT 15 . Ladder: pointer +\npulse →  auto-highlight + resume.\nSimple drag\nManipulate a representation:\ncounters into groups, fraction\npieces, a point to a tick.\nMarked zones, snap, one move\n INT 15 . Ladder: zone highlight\n→  auto-place + proceed.\nStepped / learner-\ncontrolled (post-\nMVP \nContinuous discriminations:\n88° → 91° around a right angle;\nsweeping an angle; sliding a\npoint  INT 06 .\nShow gradual change; teach the\nboundary itself, not category\nlabels.\n19. Where to Look in the Book\nRetrieval joins on the DI Knowledge Graph (skill →  page numbers →  standards).\nAppendix A of the book maps formats to CCSS. Retrieve each chapterʼs preskill\nlists, example-selection guidance, and diagnosis-and-remediation tables\nalongside the format — corrections and MCQ distractors come from the\ndocumented error patterns.\nSkill family / strand Ch. Representative formats\nCounting 4 4.1 introducing new numbers · 4.2 rational\ncounting · 4.5 count-by\nSymbol identification\n& place value 5\n5.1 5.13: numeral reading/writing, teens–\nthousands, expanded notation, column\nalignment\nBasic facts 6 6.1 plus-one facts · 6.3/6.4 fact families\nAddition 7 7.2 the slow way · 7.4 the fast way · 7.6 adding\ntwo numerals with renaming\nSubtraction 8 8.1 with lines · 8.2 teaching regrouping · 8.3 with\nrenaming · 8.5 renaming with zeros\nMultiplication 9 9.1 single digit · 9.3/9.4 multi-digit with renaming\n\nSkill family / strand Ch. Representative formats\nDivision 10 10.1 introducing division · 10.2 remainders · 10.6\ntwo-digit quotients · 10.7 rounding\nProblem solving 11 11.3 temporal sequence · 11.4 comparison · 11.5\nclassification · 11.7 multi-step\nMeasurement, time,\nmoney 12 Chapter procedures: metric/customary, telling\ntime, coins\nFractions 13 Part-whole, equivalence, operations\nDecimals 14 Reading/writing, operations, rounding\nPercent, ratio,\nprobability 15 Percent conversion; ratio tables\nData analysis 16 Graphs, tables, statistics procedures\nGeometry 17 Figures, angle work, area/perimeter/volume\nPre-algebra 18 Integers, expressions, equations;\nratio/proportion problems\n20. Example Script\nGOLDEN SCRIPT — \n21. Out of Scope & Post-MVP\n21.1 Out of scope for the videos\nIndependent practice — the mastery quiz owns ramped practice and mastery\nprogression  SEQ 13 .\nRendering, TTS/voice production, image/animation asset generation — the\nscript is their contract. Assumed player behaviors: pause/replay always\navailable; segment replay; no skip-forward until the video has been completed\nonce.\nArticle and quiz generation — same lesson card, separate generators; the\nvideo never duplicates the articleʼs faded examples or the quizʼs ramp.\n\n21.2 Post-MVP interaction types (deferred by design)\nRich drag & drop (multi-step constructions) · ordering steps · AI-graded\nfreeform explanations.\nVocal responses — deferred: reliable capture at Alpha is hard with background\nnoise.\nContinuous-adjustment / learner-controlled animations (rotate a cube; sweep\nan angle 1° 89°; step 88° → 91°). When these ship they become the preferred\nmodality for continuous discriminations  INT 06 .\n"
